Deep Security Smart Check API API Reference

Deep Security Smart Check is a container image scanner from Trend Micro.

Schemes: https
Version: 2018-05-01

Authentication

token

Deep Security Smart Check uses token-based authentication for API requests. See Sessions for APIs related to token management, then include the token in an Authorization header with the Bearer scheme: 

Authorization: Bearer {token}

type
apiKey
name
Authorization
in
header

Roles

Roles

List roles

GET /roles

Retrieve a list of roles.

expand: string all, none all
in query

A comma-separated list of attributes to expand in the results.

cursor: string (byte)
in query

An encoded value used to retrieve the next set of results for a query that returns more than limit results.

limit: integer (int64) 25
in query

The maximum number of records to return.

query: string (up to 64 chars)
in query

Space-separated strings to search for.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

200 OK

The response body contains the roles.

type
object
400 Bad Request

Something about your request didn't quite make sense. The error message should help you figure out what went wrong.

type
object
401 Unauthorized

Did you forget to include a session token in your request? You need to include

Authorization: Bearer {token}

in all requests. You can get a token from the POST /sessions API.

type
object
403 Forbidden

You tried to do something that you're not allowed to do, you naughty scamp. Check your privileges to see what you're actually allowed to do. This could also mean that your token has expired.

type
object
429 Too Many Requests

You have made too many requests too quickly. Check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object
500 Internal Server Error

Something has gone terribly wrong. Sorry! The error message may help you figure out what went wrong, but it's unlikely that you'll be able to do anything about it unless you're the server administrator. It's possible that trying again will help, but it's more likely that you're out of luck for the moment.

type
object
503 Service Unavailable

The service is temporarily unavailable, likely due to maintenance. It should be available soon, check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object

Roles

Create a role

POST /roles

Create a role.

name: string (up to 128 chars)

A name for the role.

description: string (up to 2048 chars)

A description for the role.

policies: object[]

A list of policies for the role. The total size of the policy list must be less than 32768 bytes.

object
version: string 2018-05-01

The policy format version.

statements: object[]

The list of statements in the policy.

object
effect: string allow, deny

The policy effect if the statement matches.

actions: string[]

A list of actions. Actions take the form resourceType:operation and can have a wildcard in either the resourceType or operation part. You can also use * to match all actions. The required action is listed with each API operation.

string
dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually create a record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "name": "Administrator",
  "description": "An administrator has full access to all operations.",
  "policies": [
    {
      "version": "2018-05-01",
      "statements": [
        {
          "effect": "allow",
          "actions": [
            "*"
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
200 OK

The response body contains the role details. This response will only be returned if the dryrun=true query parameter was sent.

type
object
201 Created

The response body contains the role details.

Roles

Describe a role

GET /roles/{id}

Retrieve details for a role.

expand: string all, none all
in query

A comma-separated list of attributes to expand in the results.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The system-assigned role ID.

200 OK

The response body contains the role details.

Roles

Modify a role

POST /roles/{id}

Modify a role.

name: string (up to 128 chars)

A name for the role.

description: string (up to 2048 chars)

A description for the role.

policies: object[]

A list of policies for the role. The total size of the policy list must be less than 32768 bytes.

object
version: string 2018-05-01

The policy format version.

statements: object[]

The list of statements in the policy.

object
effect: string allow, deny

The policy effect if the statement matches.

actions: string[]

A list of actions. Actions take the form resourceType:operation and can have a wildcard in either the resourceType or operation part. You can also use * to match all actions. The required action is listed with each API operation.

string
dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually modify the record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The system-assigned role ID.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "name": "Administrator",
  "description": "An administrator has full access to all operations.",
  "policies": [
    {
      "version": "2018-05-01",
      "statements": [
        {
          "effect": "allow",
          "actions": [
            "*"
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
200 OK

The response body contains the modified role details.

in all requests. You can get a token from the POST /sessions API.

It's possible that trying again will help, but it's more likely that you're out of luck for the moment.

Users

Retrieve a list of users.

expand: string all, none all
in query

cursor: string (byte)
in query

An encoded value used to retrieve the next set of results for a query that returns more than limit results.

limit: integer (int64) 25
in query

The maximum number of records to return.

query: string (up to 64 chars)
in query

Space-separated strings to search for.

The response body contains the users.

 string
Users

Create a user

POST /users

Create a user.

userID: string (up to 64 chars)

A unique name for the user.

password: string (password) (up to 1024 chars)

A password for the user.

passwordChangeRequired: boolean

If true, the user will not be able to perform any actions until they change their password.

name: string (up to 128 chars)

A display name for the user.

description: string (up to 2048 chars)

A description for the user.

role: string

The user's role ID.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually create a record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "userID": "argus",
  "password": "ThIsIsNoTaGoOdPaSsWoRd!",
  "passwordChangeRequired": false,
  "name": "Argus Panoptes",
  "description": "Guardian of the heifer Io.",
  "role": "6552eebd-5172-411e-ac71-8c323e6ca0fe"
}
200 OK

The response body contains the user details. This response will only be returned if the dryrun=true query parameter was sent.

type
object
201 Created

The response body contains the user details.

type
object
400 Bad Request

Something about your request didn't quite make sense. The error message should help you figure out what went wrong.

type
object
401 Unauthorized

Did you forget to include a session token in your request? You need to include

Authorization: Bearer {token}

in all requests. You can get a token from the POST /sessions API.

type
object
403 Forbidden

You tried to do something that you're not allowed to do, you naughty scamp. Check your privileges to see what you're actually allowed to do. This could also mean that your token has expired.

type
object
429 Too Many Requests

You have made too many requests too quickly. Check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object
500 Internal Server Error

Something has gone terribly wrong. Sorry! The error message may help you figure out what went wrong, but it's unlikely that you'll be able to do anything about it unless you're the server administrator. It's possible that trying again will help, but it's more likely that you're out of luck for the moment.

type
object
503 Service Unavailable

The service is temporarily unavailable, likely due to maintenance. It should be available soon, check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type

Users

Modify a user

POST /users/{id}

Modify a user.

userID: string (up to 64 chars)

A unique name for the user.

password: string (password) (up to 1024 chars)

A password for the user.

passwordChangeRequired: boolean

If true, the user will not be able to perform any actions until they change their password.

name: string (up to 128 chars)

A display name for the user.

description: string (up to 2048 chars)

A description for the user.

role: string

The user's role ID.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually modify the record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The system-assigned user ID.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "userID": "argus",
  "password": "ThIsIsNoTaGoOdPaSsWoRd!",
  "passwordChangeRequired": false,
  "name": "Argus Panoptes",
  "description": "Guardian of the heifer Io.",
  "role": "6552eebd-5172-411e-ac71-8c323e6ca0fe"
}
200 OK

The response body contains the user details.

Users

Delete a user

DELETE /users/{id}

Delete a user.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually delete the record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The system-assigned user ID.

200 OK

The user would be deleted if the dryrun=true parameter was not present.

204 No Content

The user has been deleted.

400 Bad Request

Something about your request didn't quite make sense. The error message should help you figure out what went wrong.

Users

Change password

POST /users/{id}/password

Change the user's password.

oldPassword: string (password) (up to 1024 chars)

The user's current password.

newPassword: string (password) (up to 1024 chars)

The user's new password.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually modify the record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The system-assigned user ID.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "oldPassword": "ThIsIsNoTaGoOdPaSsWoRd!",
  "newPassword": "ThIsIsNoTaBeTtErPaSsWoRd!"
}
200 OK

The response body contains the user details.

type
object
400 Bad Request

Something about your request didn't quite make sense. The error message should help you figure out what went wrong.

type
object
401 Unauthorized

Did you forget to include a session token in your request? You need to include

Authorization: Bearer {token}

in all requests. You can get a token from the POST /sessions API.

type
object
403 Forbidden

You tried to do something that you're not allowed to do, you naughty scamp. Check your privileges to see what you're actually allowed to do. This could also mean that your token has expired.

type
object
429 Too Many Requests

You have made too many requests too quickly. Check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object
500 Internal Server Error

Something has gone terribly wrong. Sorry! The error message may help you figure out what went wrong, but it's unlikely that you'll be able to do anything about it unless you're the server administrator. It's possible that trying again will help, but it's more likely that you're out of luck for the moment.

type
object
503 Service Unavailable

The service is temporarily unavailable, likely due to maintenance. It should be available soon, check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type

in query

cursor: string (byte)
in query

limit: integer (int64) 25
in query

The maximum number of records to return.

query: string (up to 64 chars)
in query

Sessions

Describe a session

GET /sessions/{id}

Retrieve details for a session.

expand: string all, none all
in query

A comma-separated list of attributes to expand in the results.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The system-assigned session ID.

200 OK

The response body contains the session details.

type
object
400 Bad Request

Something about your request didn't quite make sense. The error message should help you figure out what went wrong.

type
object
401 Unauthorized

Did you forget to include a session token in your request? You need to include

Authorization: Bearer {token}

in all requests. You can get a token from the POST /sessions API.

type
object
403 Forbidden

You tried to do something that you're not allowed to do, you naughty scamp. Check your privileges to see what you're actually allowed to do. This could also mean that your token has expired.

type
object
429 Too Many Requests

You have made too many requests too quickly. Check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object
500 Internal Server Error

Something has gone terribly wrong. Sorry! The error message may help you figure out what went wrong, but it's unlikely that you'll be able to do anything about it unless you're the server administrator. It's possible that trying again will help, but it's more likely that you're out of luck for the moment.

type
object
503 Service Unavailable

The service is temporarily unavailable, likely due to maintenance. It should be available soon, check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object

Sessions

Refresh a session

POST /sessions/{id}

Refresh a session. This request will refresh the session and return a new token value with a new expiry time.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually modify the record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The system-assigned session ID.

200 OK

The response body contains the refreshed session details.

Sessions

Delete a session

DELETE /sessions/{id}

Delete a session.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually delete the record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The system-assigned session ID.

200 OK

The session would be deleted if the dryrun=true parameter was not present.

204 No Content

The session has been deleted.

Something about your request didn't quite make sense. The error message should help you figure out what went wrong.

Scans

Ongoing and historical scans

Scans

List scans

GET /scans

Retrieve a list of scans. Scans are returned in descending order of creation time, so the latest scan is returned first.

expand: string all, none all
in query

A comma-separated list of attributes to expand in the results.

cursor: string (byte)
in query

An encoded value used to retrieve the next set of results for a query that returns more than limit results.

limit: integer (int64) 25
in query

The maximum number of records to return.

registry: string
in query

When present, the registry query parameter will filter the list of scans to those scans where the source.registry contains the provided value. If the exact query parameter is also provided (and true), the filter will do an exact match on the value.

repository: string
in query

When present, the repository query parameter will filter the list of scans to those scans where the source.repository contains the provided value. If the exact query parameter is also provided (and true), the filter will do an exact match on the value.

tag: string
in query

When present, the tag query parameter will filter the list of scans to those scans where the source.tag contains the provided value. If the exact query parameter is also provided (and true), the filter will do an exact match on the value.

exact: boolean
in query

When present (and true), any filtering done using the registry, repository, and tag query parameters will be done using exact matches.

status: string
in query

When present, the status query parameter will filter the list of scans to those scans where the status value contains one of the provided values. Valid values in the list are pending, in-progress, completed-with-findings, completed-no-findings, failed. Invalid values are ignored.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

digest: string
in query

When present, the digest query parameer will filter the list of scans to those scans where the image digest exactly matches the provided value.

200 OK

The response body contains the scan objects.

type
object
401 Unauthorized

Did you forget to include a session token in your request? You need to include

Authorization: Bearer {token}

in all requests. You can get a token from the POST /sessions API.

type
object
403 Forbidden

You tried to do something that you're not allowed to do, you naughty scamp. Check your privileges to see what you're actually allowed to do. This could also mean that your token has expired.

type
object
429 Too Many Requests

You have made too many requests too quickly. Check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object
500 Internal Server Error

Something has gone terribly wrong. Sorry! The error message may help you figure out what went wrong, but it's unlikely that you'll be able to do anything about it unless you're the server administrator. It's possible that trying again will help, but it's more likely that you're out of luck for the moment.

type
object
503 Service Unavailable

The service is temporarily unavailable, likely due to maintenance. It should be available soon, check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object

Scans

Create a scan

POST /scans

Create a new scan.

id: string

(optional) If you provide a request ID, the scanner will check whether it has already received another request from you with the same ID. If it has, the scanner will return 409 Conflict. If you don't provide a request ID, the scanner will create one for you.

name: string (up to 128 chars)

(optional) A descriptive name for the scan.

source: object

The source of the image to scan.

type: string docker
registry: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The registry hostname or IP address.

repository: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The repository name.

tag: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The tag of the image to scan.

credentials: object
token: string (up to 10000 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using a bearer token. Requests will include an Authorization: Bearer {token} header.

username: string (up to 128 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using basic username + password authentication. Requests will include an Authorization: Basic {encoded username + password} header.

password: string (password) (up to 10000 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using basic username + password authentication. Requests will include an Authorization: Basic {encoded username + password} header.

aws: object

The AWS-specific information for authenticating to the registry.

region: string (up to 64 chars)

The AWS region identifier for the region where the registry is located.

accessKeyID: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional AWS IAM access key identifier to use when requesting the registry authorization token. If roleID is also set, then accessKeyID is the AWS IAM access key ID used to authorize the AWS STS AssumeRole request to assume the role. If accessKeyID is not set, then the default credential chain is used.

secretAccessKey: string (up to 128 chars)

The optional AWS IAM secret access key to use when requesting the registry authorization token. If roleID is also set, then secretAccessKey is the AWS IAM secret access key used to authorize the AWS STS AssumeRole request to assume the role.

role: string (up to 2048 chars)

The optional AWS IAM role to assume when requesting the registry authorization token. If accessKeyID is also set, then accessKeyID and secretAccessKey are used to authorize the STS AssumeRole API request when assuming this role. If AccessKeyID is not set, then the default credential chain is used when assuming the role.

externalID: string (up to 1224 chars)

The optional "external ID" to use when calling the AWS STS AssumeRole API to assume the role specified in roleID. The external ID may be required by the trust policy on the role being assumed.

roleSessionName: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional "role session name" to use when calling the AWS STS AssumeRole API to assume the role specified in roleID. If roleSessionName is not provided, then DeepSecuritySmartCheck will be used.

registry: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional registry ID to use to get the registry authorization token. This can be used to access the registry in another AWS account. If not provided, the default registry will be used.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

(optional, default: false) If true, the scan will not verify TLS connections to the source URL. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the source are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the web hook will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for HTTPS source requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, source requests will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

webhooks: object[]

(optional) A list of web hooks to call when events happen for the scan.

object
name: string (up to 64 chars)

(optional) A descriptive name for the web hook.

hookURL: string (up to 255 chars)

The URL that Deep Security Smart Check should POST the event payload to.

headers: object[] (up to 10 chars)

(optional) You can include your own headers in the web hook request. Use these to provide additional context or authentication information to your web hook receiver.

object
name: string (up to 128 chars)

The header name.

value: string (up to 255 chars)

The header value.

secret: string (password) (up to 64 chars)

(optional) If you provide a secret value, then events sent over HTTP will include an X-Scan-Event-Signature header that is the SHA-256 HMAC of the event body using your secret as the key.

This value is write-only: the API will not return the secret or show that it has been set.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

(optional, default: false) If true, the web hook will not verify TLS connections to the web hook URL. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the hook URL are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the web hook will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for HTTPS web hook requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, the web hook will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

active: boolean

(optional, default: false). If true, the web hook will be invoked whenever a matching event occurs.

events: string[] (up to 10 chars)

(optional, default: ["*"]) If present, this is a list of event types that will be checked before calling the web hook. If the event type matches one of the elements of the list, the web hook will be called. If the list is empty, all events will match.

string scan-requested, scan-started, scan-completed, *
X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

Request Content-Types: application/json

Web hooks

Create a web hook

POST /webhooks

Create a new web hook.

name: string (up to 64 chars)

(optional) A descriptive name for the web hook.

hookURL: string (up to 255 chars)

The URL that Deep Security Smart Check should POST the event payload to.

headers: object[] (up to 10 chars)

(optional) You can include your own headers in the web hook request. Use these to provide additional context or authentication information to your web hook receiver.

object
name: string (up to 128 chars)

The header name.

value: string (up to 255 chars)

The header value.

secret: string (password) (up to 64 chars)

(optional) If you provide a secret value, then events sent over HTTP will include an X-Scan-Event-Signature header that is the SHA-256 HMAC of the event body using your secret as the key.

This value is write-only: the API will not return the secret or show that it has been set.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

(optional, default: false) If true, the web hook will not verify TLS connections to the web hook URL. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the hook URL are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the web hook will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for HTTPS web hook requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, the web hook will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

active: boolean

(optional, default: false). If true, the web hook will be invoked whenever a matching event occurs.

events: string[] (up to 10 chars)

(optional, default: ["*"]) If present, this is a list of event types that will be checked before calling the web hook. If the event type matches one of the elements of the list, the web hook will be called. If the list is empty, all events will match.

string scan-requested, scan-started, scan-completed, *
X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "name": "(optional) a descriptive string",
  "hookURL": "https://target.example.com/",
  "headers": [
    {
      "name": "Authorization",
      "value": "Bearer 9515e65f46cb737cd8c191db2fd80bbd05686e5992b241e8ad7727510b7142e6"
    }
  ],
  "secret": "tHiSiSaBaDsEcReT",
  "insecureSkipVerify": false,
  "rootCAs": "LS0tLS1CRUdJTiBDRVJUSUZJQ0FURS0tLS0tCi4uLiBhbmQgc28gb24gLi4uCg==",
  "active": true,
  "events": [
    "string"
  ]
}
201 Created

The web hook has been created.

object

You tried to do something that you're not allowed to do, you naughty scamp. Check your privileges to see what you're actually allowed to do. This could also mean that your token has expired.

object

You have made too many requests too quickly. Check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object
500 Internal Server Error

Something has gone terribly wrong. Sorry! The error message may help you figure out what went wrong, but it's unlikely that you'll be able to do anything about it unless you're the server administrator. It's possible that trying again will help, but it's more likely that you're out of luck for the moment.

object

The service is temporarily unavailable, likely due to maintenance. It should be available soon, check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

Content scan

Create a content scan ruleset collection

POST /collections

Add a content scan ruleset collection to manage rules. Default rules will be automatically inserted into the ruleset created.

name: string (1 to 64 chars)

The name of this ruleset collection.

default: boolean

The global ruleset collection used for content scan. There can only be one default ruleset collection at all time. If this value is true, the value of other collection will be reset to false.

rulesets: object[]

The rulesets belonging to this collection.

object
name: string (1 to 64 chars)

The name of this ruleset.

ruleset: string (up to 8192 chars)

Base64-encoded yara rules.

disabled: boolean

If set to true, this ruleset will not be used for scan.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually create a record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "name": "Smart Check collection",
  "default": true,
  "rulesets": [
    {
      "name": "Scanning rule",
      "ruleset": "cnVsZSBkZXRlY3RvciB7IAoJY29uZGl0aW9uOgoJCXRydWUKfQo=",
      "disabled": false
    }
  ]
}
200 OK

The response body contains the ruleset collection details. This response will only be returned if the dryrun=true query parameter was sent.

201 Created

The content scan ruleset has been created.

type
object
400 Bad Request

Something about your request didn't quite make sense. The error message should help you figure out what went wrong.

type
object
401 Unauthorized

Did you forget to include a session token in your request? You need to include

Authorization: Bearer {token}

in all requests. You can get a token from the POST /sessions API.

type
object
403 Forbidden

You tried to do something that you're not allowed to do, you naughty scamp. Check your privileges to see what you're actually allowed to do. This could also mean that your token has expired.

type
object
429 Too Many Requests

You have made too many requests too quickly. Check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object
500 Internal Server Error

Something has gone terribly wrong. Sorry! The error message may help you figure out what went wrong, but it's unlikely that you'll be able to do anything about it unless you're the server administrator. It's possible that trying again will help, but it's more likely that you're out of luck for the moment.

type
object
503 Service Unavailable

The service is temporarily unavailable, likely due to maintenance. It should be available soon, check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object
Response Content-Types: application/json
Response Example (201 Created) 
{
  "id": "6af2e0e1-bb7c-45b7-9a3f-152a80d154eb",
  "href": "/api/collections/60e53669-c8ef-4d0f-a8ff-3dbbb098d8ff",
  "name": "Deep Security Smart Check Collection",
  "default": true,
  "rulesets": [
    {
      "id": "6af2e0e1-bb7c-45b7-9a3f-152a80d154eb",
      "name": "Scanning ruleset",
      "href": "/api/collections/60e53669-c8ef-4d0f-a8ff-3dbbb098d8ff/rulesets/6af2e0e1-bb7c-45b7-9a3f-152a80d154eb",
      "ruleset": "cnVsZSBkZXRlY3RvciB7IAoJY29uZGl0aW9uOgoJCXRydWUKfQo=",
      "disabled": false
    }
  ]
}

Content scan

Modify a content scan ruleset collection

POST /collections/{id}

Modify a content scan ruleset collection. Rulesets cannot be modifed with this API.

name: string (1 to 64 chars)

The name of this ruleset collection.

default: boolean

The global ruleset collection used for content scan. There can only be one default ruleset collection at all time. If this value is true, the value of other collection will be reset to false.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually modify the record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

in header

id: string
in path

  "default": true
}

Content scan

Delete a content scan ruleset collection

DELETE /collections/{id}

Delete a ruleset collection and associated rulesets.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually delete the record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The collection ID.

200 OK

The ruleset collection would be deleted if the dryrun=true parameter was not present.

204 No Content

The ruleset collection has been deleted.

400 Bad Request

Something about your request didn't quite make sense. The error message should help you figure out what went wrong.

object

in all requests. You can get a token from the POST /sessions API.

object

List content scan rulesets

GET /collections/{id}/rulesets

Get the list of content scan rulesets in the indicated ruleset collection.

cursor: string (byte)
in query

An encoded value used to retrieve the next set of results for a query that returns more than limit results.

query: string (up to 64 chars)
in query

Space-separated strings to search for.

limit: integer (int64) 25
in query

The maximum number of records to return.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

id: string
in path

Content scan

Create a content scan ruleset

POST /collections/{id}/rulesets

Add a content scan ruleset to the indicated ruleset collection.

name: string (1 to 64 chars)

The name of this ruleset.

ruleset: string (up to 8192 chars)

Base64-encoded yara rules.

disabled: boolean

If set to true, this ruleset will not be used for scan.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually create a record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The ruleset ID.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "name": "Scanning rule",
  "ruleset": "cnVsZSBkZXRlY3RvciB7IAoJY29uZGl0aW9uOgoJCXRydWUKfQo=",
  "disabled": false
}
200 OK

The response body contains the ruleset details. This response will only be returned if the dryrun=true query parameter was sent.

201 Created

The content scan ruleset has been created.

Content scan

Modify a content scan ruleset

POST /collections/{id}/rulesets/{rulesetID}

Update a content scan ruleset. Built-in rulesets are not allowed to be modified except disabling/enabling.

name: string (1 to 64 chars)

The name of this ruleset.

ruleset: string (up to 8192 chars)

Base64-encoded yara rules.

disabled: boolean

If set to true, this ruleset will not be used for scan.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually modify the record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The ruleset collection ID.

rulesetID: string
in path

The ruleset ID.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "name": "Scanning rule",
  "ruleset": "cnVsZSBkZXRlY3RvciB7IAoJY29uZGl0aW9uOgoJCXRydWUKfQo=",
  "disabled": false
}
200 OK

The content scan ruleset has been updated. The response body contains the updated ruleset object.

Registries

Create a registry

POST /registries

Create a new registry connection.

name: string (up to 255 chars)

The name to display for the registry. If not specified, the registry host value will be used as the initial name.

description: string (up to 2048 chars)

A longer-form note to attach to the registry.

host: string (up to 255 chars)

The host where the registry can be found. Required except when using Amazon Elastic Container Registry.

credentials: object

Credentials to use when accessing the registry.

username: string (up to 64 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using basic username + password authentication. Requests will include an Authorization: Basic {encoded username + password} header.

password: string (password) (up to 4096 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using basic username + password authentication. Requests will include an Authorization: Basic {encoded username + password} header.

aws: object

The AWS-specific information for authenticating to the registry.

region: string (up to 64 chars)

The AWS region identifier for the region where the registry is located.

accessKeyID: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional AWS IAM access key identifier to use when requesting the registry authorization token. If roleID is also set, then accessKeyID is the AWS IAM access key ID used to authorize the AWS STS AssumeRole request to assume the role. If accessKeyID is not set, then the default credential chain is used.

secretAccessKey: string (up to 128 chars)

The optional AWS IAM secret access key to use when requesting the registry authorization token. If roleID is also set, then secretAccessKey is the AWS IAM secret access key used to authorize the AWS STS AssumeRole request to assume the role.

role: string (up to 2048 chars)

The optional AWS IAM role to assume when requesting the registry authorization token. If accessKeyID is also set, then accessKeyID and secretAccessKey are used to authorize the STS AssumeRole API request when assuming this role. If AccessKeyID is not set, then the default credential chain is used when assuming the role.

externalID: string (up to 1224 chars)

The optional "external ID" to use when calling the AWS STS AssumeRole API to assume the role specified in roleID. The external ID may be required by the trust policy on the role being assumed.

roleSessionName: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional "role session name" to use when calling the AWS STS AssumeRole API to assume the role specified in roleID. If roleSessionName is not provided, then DeepSecuritySmartCheck will be used.

registry: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional registry ID to use to get the registry authorization token. This can be used to access the registry in another AWS account. If not provided, the default registry will be used.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

If true, Deep Security Smart Check will not verify TLS connections to the registry. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the registry are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the service will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for registry requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, the service will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

filter: object

The filters that define the repositories and tags that will be synchronized from the registry. The maximum size of the filters for a registry is 32768 bytes.

include: string[] *

A pattern to use when determining which images to synchronize (include) from the registry.

string
exclude: string[]

A pattern to use when determining which images to synchronize (exclude) from the registry.

string
schedule: boolean

If true, this registry will be scheduled for daily re-scan.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually create a record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

ping: boolean true
in query

Use false to disable automatic checking of the registry host and credentials during the update.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "name": "My Registry",
  "description": "This registry is an example, and this description is similarly exemplary.\n",
  "host": "registry.example.com",
  "credentials": {
    "username": "username",
    "password": "************",
    "aws": {
      "region": "us-east-1",
      "accessKeyID": "AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE",
      "secretAccessKey": "wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY",
      "role": "arn:aws:iam::account-id:role/role-name",
      "externalID": "myExternalID",
      "roleSessionName": "DeepSecuritySmartCheck",
      "registry": "account-id"
    }
  },
  "insecureSkipVerify": false,
  "rootCAs": "LS0tLS1CRUdJTiBDRVJUSUZJQ0FURS0tLS0tCi4uLiBhbmQgc28gb24gLi4uCg==",
  "filter": {
    "include": [
      "*:latest"
    ],
    "exclude": [
      "experimental/*"
    ]
  },
  "schedule": "boolean"
}
200 OK

The response body contains the registry details. This response will only be returned if the dryrun=true query parameter was sent.

type
object
201 Created

The response body contains the registry details.

type
object
400 Bad Request

Something about your request didn't quite make sense. The error message should help you figure out what went wrong.

type
object
401 Unauthorized

Did you forget to include a session token in your request? You need to include

Authorization: Bearer {token}

in all requests. You can get a token from the POST /sessions API.

type
object
403 Forbidden

You tried to do something that you're not allowed to do, you naughty scamp. Check your privileges to see what you're actually allowed to do. This could also mean that your token has expired.

type
object
404 Not Found

The resource you were looking for doesn't exist.

type
object
409 Conflict

The preconditions in the request you made could not be met. Check the message string in the response for help troubleshooting the problem.

type
object
429 Too Many Requests

You have made too many requests too quickly. Check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object
500 Internal Server Error

Something has gone terribly wrong. Sorry! The error message may help you figure out what went wrong, but it's unlikely that you'll be able to do anything about it unless you're the server administrator. It's possible that trying again will help, but it's more likely that you're out of luck for the moment.

type
object
503 Service Unavailable

The service is temporarily unavailable, likely due to maintenance. It should be available soon, check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type

Registries

Modify a registry

POST /registries/{id}

Modify the details of a registry connection.

name: string (up to 255 chars)

The name to display for the registry. If not specified, the registry host value will be used as the initial name.

description: string (up to 2048 chars)

A longer-form note to attach to the registry.

host: string (up to 255 chars)

The host where the registry can be found. Required except when using Amazon Elastic Container Registry.

credentials: object

Credentials to use when accessing the registry.

username: string (up to 64 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using basic username + password authentication. Requests will include an Authorization: Basic {encoded username + password} header.

password: string (password) (up to 4096 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using basic username + password authentication. Requests will include an Authorization: Basic {encoded username + password} header.

aws: object

The AWS-specific information for authenticating to the registry.

region: string (up to 64 chars)

The AWS region identifier for the region where the registry is located.

accessKeyID: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional AWS IAM access key identifier to use when requesting the registry authorization token. If roleID is also set, then accessKeyID is the AWS IAM access key ID used to authorize the AWS STS AssumeRole request to assume the role. If accessKeyID is not set, then the default credential chain is used.

secretAccessKey: string (up to 128 chars)

The optional AWS IAM secret access key to use when requesting the registry authorization token. If roleID is also set, then secretAccessKey is the AWS IAM secret access key used to authorize the AWS STS AssumeRole request to assume the role.

role: string (up to 2048 chars)

The optional AWS IAM role to assume when requesting the registry authorization token. If accessKeyID is also set, then accessKeyID and secretAccessKey are used to authorize the STS AssumeRole API request when assuming this role. If AccessKeyID is not set, then the default credential chain is used when assuming the role.

externalID: string (up to 1224 chars)

The optional "external ID" to use when calling the AWS STS AssumeRole API to assume the role specified in roleID. The external ID may be required by the trust policy on the role being assumed.

roleSessionName: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional "role session name" to use when calling the AWS STS AssumeRole API to assume the role specified in roleID. If roleSessionName is not provided, then DeepSecuritySmartCheck will be used.

registry: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional registry ID to use to get the registry authorization token. This can be used to access the registry in another AWS account. If not provided, the default registry will be used.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

If true, Deep Security Smart Check will not verify TLS connections to the registry. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the registry are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the service will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for registry requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, the service will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

filter: object

The filters that define the repositories and tags that will be synchronized from the registry. The maximum size of the filters for a registry is 32768 bytes.

include: string[] *

A pattern to use when determining which images to synchronize (include) from the registry.

string
exclude: string[]

A pattern to use when determining which images to synchronize (exclude) from the registry.

string
schedule: boolean

If true, this registry will be scheduled for daily re-scan.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually modify the record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

ping: boolean true
in query

Use false to disable automatic checking of the registry host and credentials during the update.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

id: string
in path

The system-assigned registry ID.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "name": "My Registry",
  "description": "This registry is an example, and this description is similarly exemplary.\n",
  "host": "registry.example.com",
  "credentials": {
    "username": "username",
    "password": "************",
    "aws": {
      "region": "us-east-1",
      "accessKeyID": "AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE",
      "secretAccessKey": "wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY",
      "role": "arn:aws:iam::account-id:role/role-name",
      "externalID": "myExternalID",
      "roleSessionName": "DeepSecuritySmartCheck",
      "registry": "account-id"
    }
  },
  "insecureSkipVerify": false,
  "rootCAs": "LS0tLS1CRUdJTiBDRVJUSUZJQ0FURS0tLS0tCi4uLiBhbmQgc28gb24gLi4uCg==",
  "filter": {
    "include": [
      "*:latest"
    ],
    "exclude": [
      "experimental/*"
    ]
  },
  "schedule": "boolean"
}

The response body contains the registry details.

Delete a registry

Delete a registry connection.

dryrun: boolean false
in query

in path

 string
Registries

Create a scan

POST /registries/{id}/scans

Create a scan using stored registry details.

name: string (up to 128 chars)

(optional) A descriptive name for the scan.

source: object

The source of the image to scan.

repository: string (up to 255 chars)

The repository name.

tag: string (up to 255 chars)

The tag of the image to scan.

webhooks: object[]

(optional) A list of web hooks to call when events happen for the scan.

object
name: string (up to 64 chars)

(optional) A descriptive name for the web hook.

hookURL: string (up to 255 chars)

The URL that Deep Security Smart Check should POST the event payload to.

headers: object[] (up to 10 chars)

(optional) You can include your own headers in the web hook request. Use these to provide additional context or authentication information to your web hook receiver.

object
name: string (up to 128 chars)

The header name.

value: string (up to 255 chars)

The header value.

secret: string (password) (up to 64 chars)

(optional) If you provide a secret value, then events sent over HTTP will include an X-Scan-Event-Signature header that is the SHA-256 HMAC of the event body using your secret as the key.

This value is write-only: the API will not return the secret or show that it has been set.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

(optional, default: false) If true, the web hook will not verify TLS connections to the web hook URL. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the hook URL are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the web hook will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for HTTPS web hook requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, the web hook will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

active: boolean

(optional, default: false). If true, the web hook will be invoked whenever a matching event occurs.

events: string[] (up to 10 chars)

(optional, default: ["*"]) If present, this is a list of event types that will be checked before calling the web hook. If the event type matches one of the elements of the list, the web hook will be called. If the list is empty, all events will match.

string scan-requested, scan-started, scan-completed, *
dryrun: boolean false
in query

Use the dryrun=true query parameter to indicate that the request should only be tested for validity and should not actually create a record. The response code will indicate whether the request was OK (200 OK) or whether there was a problem in the request.

X-Api-Version: object 2018-05-01
in header

The version of the API to use.

Request Content-Types: application/json
Request Example
{
  "name": "(optional) a descriptive string",
  "source": {
    "repository": "organization/project",
    "tag": "latest"
  },
  "webhooks": [
    {
      "name": "(optional) a descriptive string",
      "hookURL": "https://target.example.com/",
      "headers": [
        {
          "name": "Authorization",
          "value": "Bearer 9515e65f46cb737cd8c191db2fd80bbd05686e5992b241e8ad7727510b7142e6"
        }
      ],
      "secret": "tHiSiSaBaDsEcReT",

      "active": true,
      "events": [
        "string"
      ]
    }

200 OK

The response body contains the scan details. This response will only be returned if the dryrun=true query parameter was sent.

type
object
201 Created

The response body contains the scan details.

type
object
400 Bad Request

Something about your request didn't quite make sense. The error message should help you figure out what went wrong.

type
object
401 Unauthorized

Did you forget to include a session token in your request? You need to include

Authorization: Bearer {token}

in all requests. You can get a token from the POST /sessions API.

type
object
403 Forbidden

You tried to do something that you're not allowed to do, you naughty scamp. Check your privileges to see what you're actually allowed to do. This could also mean that your token has expired.

type
object
404 Not Found

The resource you were looking for doesn't exist.

type
object
409 Conflict

The preconditions in the request you made could not be met. Check the message string in the response for help troubleshooting the problem.

type
object
429 Too Many Requests

You have made too many requests too quickly. Check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object
500 Internal Server Error

Something has gone terribly wrong. Sorry! The error message may help you figure out what went wrong, but it's unlikely that you'll be able to do anything about it unless you're the server administrator. It's possible that trying again will help, but it's more likely that you're out of luck for the moment.

type
object
503 Service Unavailable

The service is temporarily unavailable, likely due to maintenance. It should be available soon, check the Retry-After header for an indication of when you might be able to try again.

type
object

ChangeUserPasswordRequest: object

The user's current password.

The user's new password.

Example
{
  "oldPassword": "ThIsIsNoTaGoOdPaSsWoRd!",
  "newPassword": "ThIsIsNoTaBeTtErPaSsWoRd!"
}

UserRequest: object

userID: string (up to 64 chars)

A unique name for the user.

password: string (password) (up to 1024 chars)

A password for the user.

passwordChangeRequired: boolean

If true, the user will not be able to perform any actions until they change their password.

name: string (up to 128 chars)

A display name for the user.

description: string (up to 2048 chars)

A description for the user.

role: string

The user's role ID.

Example
{
  "userID": "argus",
  "password": "ThIsIsNoTaGoOdPaSsWoRd!",
  "passwordChangeRequired": false,
  "name": "Argus Panoptes",
  "description": "Guardian of the heifer Io.",
  "role": "6552eebd-5172-411e-ac71-8c323e6ca0fe"
}

RoleRequest: object

name: string (up to 128 chars)

A name for the role.

description: string (up to 2048 chars)

A description for the role.

policies: object[]

A list of policies for the role. The total size of the policy list must be less than 32768 bytes.

object
version: string 2018-05-01

The policy format version.

statements: object[]

The list of statements in the policy.

object
effect: string allow, deny

The policy effect if the statement matches.

actions: string[]

A list of actions. Actions take the form resourceType:operation and can have a wildcard in either the resourceType or operation part. You can also use * to match all actions. The required action is listed with each API operation.

string
Example
{
  "name": "Administrator",
  "description": "An administrator has full access to all operations.",
  "policies": [
    {
      "version": "2018-05-01",
      "statements": [
        {
          "effect": "allow",
          "actions": [
            "*"
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}

Error: object

message: string

The error message will explain what went wrong and will attempt to give some hints as to how to fix it.

fields: object

If present, the fields object will indicate which input fields had errors; the attribute name will be the name of the input field and the value will be an error message.

Example
{
  "message": "Something went wrong. To fix it, try ...",
  "fields": "object"
}

WebhookRequest: object

name: string (up to 64 chars)

(optional) A descriptive name for the web hook.

hookURL: string (up to 255 chars)

The URL that Deep Security Smart Check should POST the event payload to.

headers: object[] (up to 10 chars)

(optional) You can include your own headers in the web hook request. Use these to provide additional context or authentication information to your web hook receiver.

object
name: string (up to 128 chars)

The header name.

value: string (up to 255 chars)

The header value.

secret: string (password) (up to 64 chars)

(optional) If you provide a secret value, then events sent over HTTP will include an X-Scan-Event-Signature header that is the SHA-256 HMAC of the event body using your secret as the key.

This value is write-only: the API will not return the secret or show that it has been set.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

(optional, default: false) If true, the web hook will not verify TLS connections to the web hook URL. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the hook URL are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the web hook will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for HTTPS web hook requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, the web hook will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

active: boolean

(optional, default: false). If true, the web hook will be invoked whenever a matching event occurs.

events: string[] (up to 10 chars)

(optional, default: ["*"]) If present, this is a list of event types that will be checked before calling the web hook. If the event type matches one of the elements of the list, the web hook will be called. If the list is empty, all events will match.

string scan-requested, scan-started, scan-completed, *
Example
{
  "name": "(optional) a descriptive string",
  "hookURL": "https://target.example.com/",
  "headers": [
    {
      "name": "Authorization",
      "value": "Bearer 9515e65f46cb737cd8c191db2fd80bbd05686e5992b241e8ad7727510b7142e6"
    }
  ],
  "secret": "tHiSiSaBaDsEcReT",
  "insecureSkipVerify": false,
  "rootCAs": "LS0tLS1CRUdJTiBDRVJUSUZJQ0FURS0tLS0tCi4uLiBhbmQgc28gb24gLi4uCg==",
  "active": true,
  "events": [
    "string"
  ]
}

      "value": "Bearer 9515e65f46cb737cd8c191db2fd80bbd05686e5992b241e8ad7727510b7142e6"

  "insecureSkipVerify": false,
  "rootCAs": "LS0tLS1CRUdJTiBDRVJUSUZJQ0FURS0tLS0tCi4uLiBhbmQgc28gb24gLi4uCg==",

ScanRequest: object

id: string

(optional) If you provide a request ID, the scanner will check whether it has already received another request from you with the same ID. If it has, the scanner will return 409 Conflict. If you don't provide a request ID, the scanner will create one for you.

name: string (up to 128 chars)

(optional) A descriptive name for the scan.

source: object

The source of the image to scan.

type: string docker
registry: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The registry hostname or IP address.

repository: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The repository name.

tag: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The tag of the image to scan.

credentials: object
token: string (up to 10000 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using a bearer token. Requests will include an Authorization: Bearer {token} header.

username: string (up to 128 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using basic username + password authentication. Requests will include an Authorization: Basic {encoded username + password} header.

password: string (password) (up to 10000 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using basic username + password authentication. Requests will include an Authorization: Basic {encoded username + password} header.

aws: object

The AWS-specific information for authenticating to the registry.

region: string (up to 64 chars)

The AWS region identifier for the region where the registry is located.

accessKeyID: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional AWS IAM access key identifier to use when requesting the registry authorization token. If roleID is also set, then accessKeyID is the AWS IAM access key ID used to authorize the AWS STS AssumeRole request to assume the role. If accessKeyID is not set, then the default credential chain is used.

secretAccessKey: string (up to 128 chars)

The optional AWS IAM secret access key to use when requesting the registry authorization token. If roleID is also set, then secretAccessKey is the AWS IAM secret access key used to authorize the AWS STS AssumeRole request to assume the role.

role: string (up to 2048 chars)

The optional AWS IAM role to assume when requesting the registry authorization token. If accessKeyID is also set, then accessKeyID and secretAccessKey are used to authorize the STS AssumeRole API request when assuming this role. If AccessKeyID is not set, then the default credential chain is used when assuming the role.

externalID: string (up to 1224 chars)

The optional "external ID" to use when calling the AWS STS AssumeRole API to assume the role specified in roleID. The external ID may be required by the trust policy on the role being assumed.

roleSessionName: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional "role session name" to use when calling the AWS STS AssumeRole API to assume the role specified in roleID. If roleSessionName is not provided, then DeepSecuritySmartCheck will be used.

registry: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional registry ID to use to get the registry authorization token. This can be used to access the registry in another AWS account. If not provided, the default registry will be used.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

(optional, default: false) If true, the scan will not verify TLS connections to the source URL. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the source are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the web hook will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for HTTPS source requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, source requests will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

webhooks: object[]

(optional) A list of web hooks to call when events happen for the scan.

object
name: string (up to 64 chars)

(optional) A descriptive name for the web hook.

hookURL: string (up to 255 chars)

The URL that Deep Security Smart Check should POST the event payload to.

headers: object[] (up to 10 chars)

(optional) You can include your own headers in the web hook request. Use these to provide additional context or authentication information to your web hook receiver.

object
name: string (up to 128 chars)

The header name.

value: string (up to 255 chars)

The header value.

secret: string (password) (up to 64 chars)

(optional) If you provide a secret value, then events sent over HTTP will include an X-Scan-Event-Signature header that is the SHA-256 HMAC of the event body using your secret as the key.

This value is write-only: the API will not return the secret or show that it has been set.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

(optional, default: false) If true, the web hook will not verify TLS connections to the web hook URL. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the hook URL are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the web hook will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for HTTPS web hook requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, the web hook will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

active: boolean

(optional, default: false). If true, the web hook will be invoked whenever a matching event occurs.

events: string[] (up to 10 chars)

(optional, default: ["*"]) If present, this is a list of event types that will be checked before calling the web hook. If the event type matches one of the elements of the list, the web hook will be called. If the list is empty, all events will match.

string scan-requested, scan-started, scan-completed, *
Example
{
  "id": "(optional) any unique string",
  "name": "(optional) a descriptive string",
  "source": {
    "type": "string",
    "registry": "registry.example.com",
    "repository": "organization/project",
    "tag": "latest",
    "credentials": {
      "token": "9515e65f46cb737cd8c191db2fd80bbd05686e5992b241e8ad7727510b7142e6",
      "username": "username",
      "password": "************",
      "aws": {
        "region": "us-east-1",
        "accessKeyID": "AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE",
        "secretAccessKey": "wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY",
        "role": "arn:aws:iam::account-id:role/role-name",
        "externalID": "myExternalID",
        "roleSessionName": "DeepSecuritySmartCheck",
        "registry": "account-id"
      }
    },
    "insecureSkipVerify": false,
    "rootCAs": "LS0tLS1CRUdJTiBDRVJUSUZJQ0FURS0tLS0tCi4uLiBhbmQgc28gb24gLi4uCg=="
  },
  "webhooks": [
    {
      "name": "(optional) a descriptive string",
      "hookURL": "https://target.example.com/",
      "headers": [
        {
          "name": "Authorization",
          "value": "Bearer 9515e65f46cb737cd8c191db2fd80bbd05686e5992b241e8ad7727510b7142e6"
        }
      ],
      "secret": "tHiSiSaBaDsEcReT",
      "insecureSkipVerify": false,
      "rootCAs": "LS0tLS1CRUdJTiBDRVJUSUZJQ0FURS0tLS0tCi4uLiBhbmQgc28gb24gLi4uCg==",
      "active": true,
      "events": [
        "string"
      ]
    }
  ]
}

SourceRequest: object

The source of the image to scan.

type: string docker
registry: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The registry hostname or IP address.

repository: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The repository name.

tag: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The tag of the image to scan.

credentials: object
token: string (up to 10000 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using a bearer token. Requests will include an Authorization: Bearer {token} header.

username: string (up to 128 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using basic username + password authentication. Requests will include an Authorization: Basic {encoded username + password} header.

password: string (password) (up to 10000 chars)

(optional) Use this if your source requires requests to be authorized using basic username + password authentication. Requests will include an Authorization: Basic {encoded username + password} header.

aws: object

The AWS-specific information for authenticating to the registry.

region: string (up to 64 chars)

The AWS region identifier for the region where the registry is located.

accessKeyID: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional AWS IAM access key identifier to use when requesting the registry authorization token. If roleID is also set, then accessKeyID is the AWS IAM access key ID used to authorize the AWS STS AssumeRole request to assume the role. If accessKeyID is not set, then the default credential chain is used.

secretAccessKey: string (up to 128 chars)

The optional AWS IAM secret access key to use when requesting the registry authorization token. If roleID is also set, then secretAccessKey is the AWS IAM secret access key used to authorize the AWS STS AssumeRole request to assume the role.

role: string (up to 2048 chars)

The optional AWS IAM role to assume when requesting the registry authorization token. If accessKeyID is also set, then accessKeyID and secretAccessKey are used to authorize the STS AssumeRole API request when assuming this role. If AccessKeyID is not set, then the default credential chain is used when assuming the role.

externalID: string (up to 1224 chars)

The optional "external ID" to use when calling the AWS STS AssumeRole API to assume the role specified in roleID. The external ID may be required by the trust policy on the role being assumed.

roleSessionName: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional "role session name" to use when calling the AWS STS AssumeRole API to assume the role specified in roleID. If roleSessionName is not provided, then DeepSecuritySmartCheck will be used.

registry: string (up to 64 chars)

The optional registry ID to use to get the registry authorization token. This can be used to access the registry in another AWS account. If not provided, the default registry will be used.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

(optional, default: false) If true, the scan will not verify TLS connections to the source URL. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the source are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the web hook will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for HTTPS source requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, source requests will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

Example
{
  "type": "string",
  "registry": "registry.example.com",
  "repository": "organization/project",
  "tag": "latest",
  "credentials": {
    "token": "9515e65f46cb737cd8c191db2fd80bbd05686e5992b241e8ad7727510b7142e6",
    "username": "username",
    "password": "************",
    "aws": {
      "region": "us-east-1",
      "accessKeyID": "AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE",
      "secretAccessKey": "wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY",
      "role": "arn:aws:iam::account-id:role/role-name",
      "externalID": "myExternalID",
      "roleSessionName": "DeepSecuritySmartCheck",
      "registry": "account-id"
    }
  },
  "insecureSkipVerify": false,
  "rootCAs": "LS0tLS1CRUdJTiBDRVJUSUZJQ0FURS0tLS0tCi4uLiBhbmQgc28gb24gLi4uCg=="
}

Source: object

type: string docker
registry: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The registry hostname or IP address.

repository: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The repository name.

tag: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The tag of the image to scan.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

(optional, default: false) If true, the scan will not verify TLS connections to the source URL. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the source are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the web hook will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for HTTPS web hook requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, the web hook will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

{

  "rootCAs": "LS0tLS1CRUdJTiBDRVJUSUZJQ0FURS0tLS0tCi4uLiBhbmQgc28gb24gLi4uCg=="
}

Scan: object

id: string

The unique ID assigned to this scan.

href: string

The URL to the scan resource.

name: string (up to 128 chars)

If you provided a name for the scan, it will be returned here.

source: object
type: string docker
registry: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The registry hostname or IP address.

repository: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The repository name.

tag: string (up to 255 chars)

(for scan type docker only) The tag of the image to scan.

insecureSkipVerify: boolean

(optional, default: false) If true, the scan will not verify TLS connections to the source URL. Use this only in controlled environments where you know that connections between the Deep Security Smart Check scanner and the source are secured by other means.

rootCAs: string (up to 32768 chars)

(optional, default: null) If present, the web hook will use the provided root CAs as the trusted root CAs for HTTPS web hook requests. The value should be a base-64 encoded list of PEM-encoded certificates. If not present, the web hook will use a set of built-in trusted root CAs. If insecureSkipVerify is set to true, then the root CAs are not checked.

status: string pending, in-progress, completed-with-findings, completed-no-findings, failed
details: object
detail: string

(optional) More details about the scan status.

requested: string (date-time)

The time that the scan was requested.

started: string (date-time)

The time that the scan started. This value will not be present if the scan has not yet started.

updated: string (date-time)

The time that the scan was last updated. This value will not be present if the scan has not yet started.

completed: string (date-time)

The time that the scan completed. This value will not be present if the scan has not yet completed.

digest: string

The image digest for the scanned image. This value will only be present for Docker scans.

os: string

The target operating system for the scanned image. This value will only be present for Docker scans.

architecture: string

The target architecture for the scanned image. This value will only be present for Docker scans.

labels: object

The labels associated with the scanned image. This value will only be present for Docker scans.

results: object[]
object
id: string

A layer identifier. For scans of type docker, this will be the layer's digest value. This attribute will not be present for scans of type http.

createdAt: string (date-time)

For scans of Docker images, this attribute will show the time at which the layer was created.

createdBy: string

For scans of Docker images, this attribute will show the Docker daemon command that ran to create this layer. This is not an exact match to the Dockerfile line, but will help to provide better context of the results.

malware: string

If present, a URL pointing to the list of malware that was found. See listScanLayerMalware.

vulnerabilities: string

If present, a URL pointing to the list of vulnerabilities that were found. See listScanLayerVulnerabilities.

contents: string

If present, a URL pointing to the list of content scan results that were found. See listScanLayerVulnerabilities.

findings: object
scanners: object

Metadata about the scanners that produced the results.

malware: object

Metadata for the malware scanner.

status: string ok, unavailable

Availability of the malware scanner.

updated: string (date-time)

The time that the malware pattern database was last updated.

versions: object
icrc: string

The ICRC pattern version.

trendX: string

The TrendX pattern version.

blacklist: string

The malware blacklist pattern version.

vulnerabilities: object

Metadata for the vulnerability scanner.

status: string ok, unavailable

Availability of the vulnerability scanner.

updated: string (date-time)

The time that the vulnerabilities database was last updated.

vulnerabilityPatterns: object

Metadata for the vulnerability pattern scanner.

status: string ok, unavailable

Availability of the vulnerability pattern scanner.

date: string (date-time)

The time that the vulnerability patterns were last published.

updated: string (date-time)

The time that the vulnerability patterns were last synchronized from the vulnerability feed.

malware: integer

The number of malware items that were found. high:

contents: object

The number of content findings found by severity.

total: object

The total number of content findings categorized by severity.

defcon1: integer

The number of "Defcon1" content findings that were found.

critical: integer

The number of critical content findings that were found.

high: integer

The number of high-severity content findings that were found.

medium: integer

The number of medium-severity content findings that were found.

low: integer

The number of low-severity content findings that were found.

negligible: integer

The number of negligible content findings that were found.

unknown: integer

The number of content findings with unknown severity that were found.

vulnerabilities: object

The number of vulnerabilities found by severity.

total: object

The total number of vulnerabilities that were found by severity.

defcon1: integer

The number of "Defcon1" vulnerabilities that were found.

critical: integer

The number of critical vulnerabilities that were found.

high: integer

The number of high-severity vulnerabilities that were found.

medium: integer

The number of medium-severity vulnerabilities that were found.

low: integer

The number of low-severity vulnerabilities that were found.

negligible: integer

The number of negligible vulnerabilities that were found.

unknown: integer

The number of vulnerabilities with unknown severity that were found.

unresolved: object

The number of unresolved vulnerabilities that were found by severity. Unresolved vulnerabilities are vulnerabilities that were found in a layer and were not fixed by an update in a subsequent layer.

defcon1: integer

The number of "Defcon1" vulnerabilities that were found.

critical: integer
